	<h3>Process</h3>
	<p>Design scale.<sup>1</sup> Cut wax into chunks. Use available molds for primary chunks. Flask for wings. Lightbulb for engines. Pistol for hull. Melt with butane torch.<sup>2</sup> Attach to tree.<sup>3</sup> Place in wire cylindrical plaster mesh.<sup>4</sup> Place in furnace (kiln) upside down to melt wax from cured mold. Pour liquid bronze into openings.<sup>5</sup> Allow to cool in sand pit. (Sand supports plaster and insulates.) Shock warm molds in water. Bust out of plaster.<sup>6</sup> Wire brush cruft.<sup>7</sup> Angle grind off branches.<sup>8</sup> Sand blast for final texture.<sup>9</sup></p>
	
	<h3>Reflection</h3>
	<p>Modifying wax easier than bronze. Build well-supported tree. Bronze is unpredictable once poured. Right tools for the job.</p>